---

<SiteLayout site="firemaths" title="Income Tax Calculator: Find Your True Take-Home Pay" description="Stop guessing how much of your paycheck you actually keep. Calculate your true net income after federal, Social Security, and Medicare taxes..." canonical="https://firemaths.info/income-tax-calculator" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Net Income Tax Calculator</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Calculate your take-home pay after federal and FICA payroll taxes.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="calculator-container">
      <div style="display: grid; gap: 1.5rem; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; margin-bottom: 2rem;">
        <div>
          <label for="grossIncome" style="display: block; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Gross Annual Salary ($)</label>
          <input type="number" id="grossIncome" value="85000" min="0" step="1000" placeholder="e.g. 85000" />
          <p id="incomeError" style="color: #ef4444; font-size: 0.85rem; margin-top: 0.5rem; display: none;">Please enter a valid positive number.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <label for="filingStatus" style="display: block; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Filing Status</label>
          <select id="filingStatus">
            <option value="single">Single</option>
            <option value="marriedJoint">Married Filing Jointly</option>
            <option value="headOfHousehold">Head of Household</option>
          </select>
        </div>
        <div style="grid-column: 1 / -1;">
          <label for="taxYear" style="display: block; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Tax Year</label>
          <select id="taxYear">
            <option value="2024">2024</option>
            <option value="2025" selected>2025</option>
          </select>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="result-card">
        <p style="font-size: 1.2rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; font-weight: 600;">Estimated Annual Take-Home Pay</p>
        <div class="result-value" id="takeHomeDisplay">$0</div>

        <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr 1fr; gap: 1rem; margin-top: 1.5rem; background: var(--bg-color); padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);">
          <div>
            <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--text-secondary); margin-bottom: 0.25rem;">Total Federal Tax</p>
            <p style="font-weight: 700; font-size: 1.2rem; color: #ef4444;" id="federalTaxDisplay">$0</p>
          </div>
          <div style="border-left: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-right: 1px solid var(--border-color);">
            <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--text-secondary); margin-bottom: 0.25rem;">FICA Taxes</p>
            <p style="font-weight: 700; font-size: 1.2rem; color: #ef4444;" id="ficaTaxDisplay">$0</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--text-secondary); margin-bottom: 0.25rem;">Monthly Take-Home</p>
            <p style="font-weight: 700; font-size: 1.2rem; color: var(--accent-color);" id="monthlyTakeHomeDisplay">$0</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p style="text-align: center; font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--text-secondary); margin-top: 1rem;">
        *Calculations assume the standard deduction. Does not include state income taxes, local taxes, or voluntary deductions like 401(k) contributions. Just looking for federal brackets? See our <a href="/tax-calculator" style="color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: underline;">Federal Tax Calculator</a>.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="explainer">
      <h2>Decoding Your Paycheck: Gross vs. Net Income</h2>
      <p>Landing a job with a $100,000 salary sounds fantastic—until you receive your first paycheck and wonder where a massive chunk of your money went. The gap between your gross salary and your take-home pay is driven by a complex web of taxes. An accurate <strong>income tax calculator</strong> bridges this gap, allowing you to accurately budget, forecast your FIRE numbers, and understand your true earning power.</p>

      <h3>The Big Three Deductions</h3>
      <p>When calculating your net income, our tool accounts for the three primary mandatory federal deductions:</p>

      <h4>1. Federal Income Tax</h4>
      <p>This is the progressive tax applied to your taxable income. Depending on whether you use the <strong>income tax calculator 2024</strong> or <strong>income tax calculator 2025</strong> parameters, the exact bracket thresholds shift due to inflation. This tax is calculated <em>after</em> the standard deduction is removed from your gross income.</p>

      <h4>2. Social Security Tax (FICA)</h4>
      <p>Part of the Federal Insurance Contributions Act, the Social Security tax is a flat 6.2% levied on your wages. However, unlike the income tax, there is an income cap. For 2024, the wage base limit is $168,600. Any income earned above this threshold is not subject to the 6.2% Social Security tax. Our <strong>income calculator tax</strong> algorithm automatically accounts for this cap.</p>

      <h4>3. Medicare Tax (FICA)</h4>
      <p>The second half of FICA is the Medicare tax. This is a flat 1.45% tax applied to all your wages. Unlike Social Security, there is no income cap for Medicare. In fact, if you earn over a certain threshold ($200,000 for single filers, $250,000 for married filing jointly), you are subject to an Additional Medicare Tax of 0.9% on the excess earnings.</p>

      <h3>Why an Income Tax Chart Isn't Enough</h3>
      <p>Many people try to estimate their take-home pay by looking at an <strong>income tax chart</strong>, finding their marginal bracket, and simply multiplying. For instance, if you're in the 22% bracket, you might assume you lose 22% of your entire check to taxes. This methodology is fundamentally flawed for two reasons:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Progressive Brackets:</strong> Federal taxes are tiered. You pay 10% on the first chunk of income, 12% on the next, and so on. You only pay 22% on the dollars that fall <em>within</em> that specific bracket.</li>
        <li><strong>Missing Taxes:</strong> An income tax chart ignores FICA taxes entirely. Even if your effective federal income tax rate is surprisingly low, the combined 7.65% from Social Security and Medicare guarantees a significant bite out of your gross pay.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Using an Income Tax Tracker for FIRE</h3>
      <p>For those pursuing Financial Independence, tracking your true net income is paramount. Your savings rate—the core metric of FIRE—is calculated based on your net take-home pay, not your gross salary. Utilizing an <strong>income tax tracker</strong> or checking an updated calculator annually helps you optimize your pre-tax investments (like a 401k or traditional IRA), which lower your taxable income and increase your overall tax efficiency.</p>

      <h3>Looking Ahead: Income Tax Calculator 2026</h3>
      <p>Because inflation pushes the standard deduction and tax brackets higher every year, your take-home pay on the exact same salary will technically increase slightly from year to year (assuming tax laws don't change). The <strong>income tax calculator 2026</strong> will reflect these future inflation adjustments once the IRS publishes the finalized data late next year.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>Why is my take-home pay lower than my gross income minus federal tax?</summary>
        <p>Your take-home pay is affected by more than just federal income tax. You must also account for FICA taxes (Social Security at 6.2% and Medicare at 1.45%), state income taxes, and pre-tax deductions like 401(k) contributions or health insurance premiums.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the income tax calculator 2025 based on?</summary>
        <p>Our income tax calculator 2025 uses the official IRS inflation-adjusted tax brackets and standard deductions projected for the 2025 tax year. It also incorporates the current FICA (Federal Insurance Contributions Act) tax rates.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can I use an income tax chart to find my exact net income?</summary>
        <p>An income tax chart provides a broad overview of marginal tax brackets, but it cannot accurately calculate your net income because it doesn't account for standard deductions, FICA limits, or your specific filing status. You need a dedicated income tax calculator for precise numbers.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How does an income tax tracker help with budgeting?</summary>
        <p>By using an income tax tracker or an income calculator tax tool throughout the year, you can verify that your employer is withholding the correct amount. If your withholdings are off, you can submit a new W-4 to avoid a massive tax bill in April or prevent giving the government a free loan.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Will there be changes to the income tax calculator 2026?</summary>
        <p>Yes, the income tax calculator 2026 will be updated late in 2025 once the IRS releases the new inflation-adjusted brackets and standard deductions, as well as any changes to the Social Security wage base limit.</p>
      </details>
    </section>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    const taxData = {
      2024: {
        standardDeduction: { single: 14600, marriedJoint: 29200, headOfHousehold: 21900 },
        ssLimit: 168600,
        medicareSurtaxThreshold: { single: 200000, marriedJoint: 250000, headOfHousehold: 200000 },
        brackets: {
          single: [
            { rate: 0.10, upTo: 11600 },
            { rate: 0.12, upTo: 47150 },
            { rate: 0.22, upTo: 100525 },
            { rate: 0.24, upTo: 191950 },
            { rate: 0.32, upTo: 243725 },
            { rate: 0.35, upTo: 609350 },
            { rate: 0.37, upTo: Infinity }
          ],
          marriedJoint: [
            { rate: 0.10, upTo: 23200 },
            { rate: 0.12, upTo: 94300 },
            { rate: 0.22, upTo: 201050 },
            { rate: 0.24, upTo: 383900 },
            { rate: 0.32, upTo: 487450 },
            { rate: 0.35, upTo: 731200 },
            { rate: 0.37, upTo: Infinity }
          ],
          headOfHousehold: [
            { rate: 0.10, upTo: 16550 },
            { rate: 0.12, upTo: 63100 },
            { rate: 0.22, upTo: 100500 },
            { rate: 0.24, upTo: 191950 },
            { rate: 0.32, upTo: 243700 },
            { rate: 0.35, upTo: 609350 },
            { rate: 0.37, upTo: Infinity }
          ]
        }
      },
      2025: {
        standardDeduction: { single: 15000, marriedJoint: 30000, headOfHousehold: 22500 },
        ssLimit: 176100, // Estimated/Projected for 2025
        medicareSurtaxThreshold: { single: 200000, marriedJoint: 250000, headOfHousehold: 200000 },
        brackets: {
          single: [
            { rate: 0.10, upTo: 11925 },
            { rate: 0.12, upTo: 48475 },
            { rate: 0.22, upTo: 103350 },
            { rate: 0.24, upTo: 197300 },
            { rate: 0.32, upTo: 250525 },
            { rate: 0.35, upTo: 626350 },
            { rate: 0.37, upTo: Infinity }
          ],
          marriedJoint: [
            { rate: 0.10, upTo: 23850 },
            { rate: 0.12, upTo: 96950 },
            { rate: 0.22, upTo: 206700 },
            { rate: 0.24, upTo: 394600 },
            { rate: 0.32, upTo: 501050 },
            { rate: 0.35, upTo: 751600 },
            { rate: 0.37, upTo: Infinity }
          ],
          headOfHousehold: [
            { rate: 0.10, upTo: 17000 },
            { rate: 0.12, upTo: 64850 },
            { rate: 0.22, upTo: 103350 },
            { rate: 0.24, upTo: 197300 },
            { rate: 0.32, upTo: 250500 },
            { rate: 0.35, upTo: 626350 },
            { rate: 0.37, upTo: Infinity }
          ]
        }
      }
    };

    const incomeInput = document.getElementById('grossIncome');
    const filingStatusSelect = document.getElementById('filingStatus');
    const taxYearSelect = document.getElementById('taxYear');
    const incomeError = document.getElementById('incomeError');

    const takeHomeDisplay = document.getElementById('takeHomeDisplay');
    const federalTaxDisplay = document.getElementById('federalTaxDisplay');
    const ficaTaxDisplay = document.getElementById('ficaTaxDisplay');
    const monthlyTakeHomeDisplay = document.getElementById('monthlyTakeHomeDisplay');

    function formatCurrency(num) {
      return new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', { style: 'currency', currency: 'USD', maximumFractionDigits: 0 }).format(num);
    }

    function calculateTaxes() {
      const grossIncome = parseFloat(incomeInput.value);

      if (isNaN(grossIncome) || grossIncome < 0) {
        incomeError.style.display = 'block';
        takeHomeDisplay.textContent = '$0';
        federalTaxDisplay.textContent = '$0';
        ficaTaxDisplay.textContent = '$0';
        monthlyTakeHomeDisplay.textContent = '$0';
        return;
      }

      incomeError.style.display = 'none';

      const year = taxYearSelect.value;
      const status = filingStatusSelect.value;
      const data = taxData[year];

      // Calculate FICA
      const ssTaxable = Math.min(grossIncome, data.ssLimit);
      const socialSecurityTax = ssTaxable * 0.062;

      let medicareTax = grossIncome * 0.0145;
      const surtaxThreshold = data.medicareSurtaxThreshold[status];
      if (grossIncome > surtaxThreshold) {
        medicareTax += (grossIncome - surtaxThreshold) * 0.009; // 0.9% additional medicare tax
      }

      const totalFica = socialSecurityTax + medicareTax;

      // Calculate Federal Income Tax
      const deduction = data.standardDeduction[status];
      let taxableIncome = Math.max(0, grossIncome - deduction);
      let totalFedTax = 0;
      let previousUpTo = 0;

      const brackets = data.brackets[status];

      if (taxableIncome > 0) {
        for (let i = 0; i < brackets.length; i++) {
          const bracket = brackets[i];
          const taxableInThisBracket = Math.min(taxableIncome - previousUpTo, bracket.upTo - previousUpTo);

          if (taxableInThisBracket > 0) {
            totalFedTax += taxableInThisBracket * bracket.rate;
          }

          previousUpTo = bracket.upTo;
          if (taxableIncome <= bracket.upTo) break;
        }
      }

      const totalTax = totalFedTax + totalFica;
      const netIncome = Math.max(0, grossIncome - totalTax);
      const monthlyTakeHome = netIncome / 12;

      takeHomeDisplay.textContent = formatCurrency(netIncome);
      federalTaxDisplay.textContent = formatCurrency(totalFedTax);
      ficaTaxDisplay.textContent = formatCurrency(totalFica);
      monthlyTakeHomeDisplay.textContent = formatCurrency(monthlyTakeHome);
    }

    ['input', 'change'].forEach(evt => {
      incomeInput.addEventListener(evt, calculateTaxes);
    });
    filingStatusSelect.addEventListener('change', calculateTaxes);
    taxYearSelect.addEventListener('change', calculateTaxes);

    // Initial calculation
    calculateTaxes();
  </script>

